{{italic title}} {{distinguish|R v Dudley and Stephens}} '''''R v Stephens''''' (1866) LR 1 QB 702 is an [[English criminal law]], [[English land law|land law]] and [[UK public law]] case decided by the [[Queen's Bench]] that applied a [[strict liability]] standard to the violation of a [[crime|criminal]] [[statute]] prohibiting the dumping of refuse into a river.
==Facts== The defendant owned a quarry where refuse was dumped into a nearby river. The owner claimed he had no knowledge of the dumping and so should not be liable.
==Judgment== The defendant quarry owner was held criminally [[liable]] even though he had no knowledge of the dumping.<ref>Bonnie, R.J. et al. ''Criminal Law, Second Edition.'' Foundation Press, New York, NY: 2004, p. 252</ref>
